A '''tridecahedron''' is a [[polyhedron]] with 13 [[Face (geometry)|faces]]. There are numerous topologically distinct forms of a tridecahedron, for example the [[dodecagonal pyramid]] and [[hendecagonal prism]].
==Convex==

There are 96,262,938 topologically distinct ''convex'' tridecahedra, excluding mirror images, having at least 9 vertices.<ref>[http://www.numericana.com/data/polycount.htm Counting polyhedra]</ref> (Two polyhedra are "topologically distinct" if they have intrinsically different arrangements of faces and vertices, such that it is impossible to distort one into the other simply by changing the lengths of edges or the angles between edges or faces.) There is a pseudo-[[space-filling polyhedron|space-filling tridecahedron]] that can fill all of 3-space together with its mirror-image.<ref name="Ludacer">{{cite web |last1=Ludacer |first1=Randy |title=Honeycombs and Structural Package Design: More Ways of Taking Up Space |url=http://www.beachpackagingdesign.com/wp/2011/09/honeycombs-and-structural-package-design-more-ways-of-taking-up-space.html |website=Beach Branding & Packaging Design |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307203424/http://beachpackagingdesign.com/boxvox/honeycombs-and-structural-package-design-more-ways-of-taking-up-space |archivedate=2016-03-07}}</ref>

